Exfoliating Night Skincare Routine ✨

Hey guys in today’s video I’m doing skincare routine for your exfoliating nights. 

Exfoliating with peeling solution, can leave your skin looking brighter and improve the effectiveness of your skincare. 

Regular exfoliating can help
Prevent clogged pores and blackheads. 

Step 1 use a mild cleanser, @dermavive_india is very gentle and doesn’t rip the natural moisture from your skin. 

Step 2 use a peeling solution, @drsheths medium peel deeply exfoliates and brightens your skin for a smoother complexion. 

Apply a thick layer and leave it on only for 8-10 mins do not leave it on for more than that. It might tinkle a bit but that’s very common. 

Use only at nights, use it only once in two weeks or once a week maximum. Do not over use, over exfoliating will break your skin barrier. 

Do not use any skincare acids for the next 24 hours if using. 
It’s formulated with lactic acid / glycolic acid and salicylic acid. 

It reduces the appearance of pores, dark spots, blackheads and whiteheads. 

If your above the age 25, you can start using peeling solution. 
It’s NOT PREGNANCY SAFE. 

Now finish it off with a thick layer of aloe Vera @bubblefarmindia gel or any mild moisturiser. 
And don’t forget to use sunscreen the next morning. 

Since the layer of dead skin cells is removed your skin tends to become more sensitive to sunlight which is why it’s important you wear SPF. 

You can use my code Mercy20 on @drsheths website 💜

#keepingitreal 

Taking care of your hair and skin from the inside out requires a combination of healthy habits, proper nutrition, and a balanced lifestyle.

1. Nutrition for Hair and Skin Health
	Hydration: Drink at least 2-3 liters of water daily to keep your skin and hair hydrated.
	Protein: Include protein-rich foods like eggs, lentils, fish, and nuts for strong hair and glowing skin.
	Healthy Fats: Incorporate omega-3 fatty acids (found in salmon, walnuts, and flaxseeds) for supple skin and hair.
	Vitamin E: Present in almonds and sunflower seeds for skin repair and protection.
	Biotin (Vitamin B7): Supports hair growth and skin health; found in eggs, nuts, and sweet potatoes.
	Zinc & Iron: Found in leafy greens, beans, and whole grains to prevent hair loss and promote skin repair.
	Antioxidants: Add berries, green tea, and dark chocolate to fight oxidative stress.

2. Lifestyle Practices
	•	Adequate Sleep: Aim for 7-8 hours of quality sleep to allow skin and hair to regenerate.
	Exercise: Regular physical activity improves blood circulation, giving skin a natural glow and promoting healthy hair follicles.
	Stress Management: Practice mindfulness, yoga, or meditation to reduce cortisol levels, which can damage hair and skin.

3. Daily Habits
	Limit Sugar: High sugar levels can lead to dull skin and hair.
	Avoid Smoking and Excessive Alcohol: These habits dehydrate your skin and weaken hair.

4. Supplements : 
	Consult a healthcare professional before taking supplements like biotin, collagen, or omega-3 capsules. Ask for a blood test to see check your vitamin levels!

Share if you are a proud Indian 🇮🇳

This was a last minute trip, we wanted to go somewhere for this Pongal holidays, we decided in the morning and left to Kashmir 11 pm on the same day. 

Winters at Kashmir was a different experience, and it seems during summer it will be a different experience. 

Day 1 - We reached Srinagar and visited Dal Lake Skilala Ride, it’s got a beautiful floating market and did all things touristy. 

Day 2 - Gulmarg, it’s completely snow covered, it’s a 2 hour ride from Srinagar. 
It’s got so many snow activities and it was truly fun. The Gondola Ride is a must visit. 

Day 3- Pahalgam, it’s a 3 hour drive from Srinagar. It’s called as Mini Switzerland, it looked breathtaking. The only way to visit the mountain peak is through a horse. You cannot walk or use any other mode of transportation. I do not recommend this for kids and older people since it’s full black ice and very slippery. It might be adventurous for us but I don’t think it’s a good idea for kids especially during winters. 

Day 4- Doodhpathri, it’s called a valley of milk. During winter the whole valley is frozen and looks like milk. 
Most of these places you will have to go only by horse, since it’s a mountain top and there are no roads, only horses are used as transportation. 
During winters it might be slightly difficult but I guess during summers it will be safe.
